This paper is primarily focused on programming language theory and semantics, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with effect systems, which are a type of static analysis for reasoning about the behavior of programs, making cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) another likely sub-category. The paper also discusses domain-theoretic denotational semantics, which is a mathematical approach to semantics, suggesting that cs.THEORY (Theoretical Computer Science) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the development of tools for finding contextual equivalences, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.SE (Software Engineering) or cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) sub-categories.
